<div id="Idea_3714"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/3714-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_3714">Require Legislators to Read and Understand Legislation before Voting on it.&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/7383-4049">quality</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">3 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">This seems logical, and yet bills with sweeping consequences, sometimes numbering in the hundreds of pages, are printed when there is no time for anyone to read the bill, let alone intelligently consider it, before voting.   Constitution-bending pieces of legislation have been bullied into passage with a lot of noise about how we can't wait to pass it, even though we have to live with the consequences for years after it is passed.  This is how the Patriot Act was passed, for instance.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_3714" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_3714', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2237&topicID=3714')">Comments (5)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_3714"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2237">Making Government Operations More Open</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=legislation">legislation</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_3714"></div>
